snippet.textDisplay:
Here’s the thing with the spanking thing. As a child I figured out that my mom had literally zero power over me, hid my games,I found them. said I couldn’t go hang out with friends, did it anyway. Told to go have a time out just didn’t do it and a parent who only uses verbal consequences for actions has no power once the child figures out they don’t have to obey commands.

My mom started to spank me as a consequence instead, I didn’t like it and I now understand why she did it. I changed my actions pretty quick because there was now a consequence I couldn’t avoid. I don’t think it should be a primary form of punishment, it is however necessary.

If you are a strict parent your kids will most likely lie to you very often.

snippet.textDisplay: my parents are very strict, but, since i'm an adult (in my culture we stay close with parents/live with them for a while, but i'm not even into my 20s so) they let me do whatever if i am responsible for it. i buy it if i want to fly somewhere, i drive and share location if i am meeting someone, i buy fast food, i stay up too late and am tired the next day at work. they were strict as a child though, but now, they allow whatever i am completely responsible for. still strict but good. i do disagree with hitting kids though. boundaries are safe. adults do know best. don't isolate the child, hurt the child, etc. use words and be set in them. foster child's passions and if they veer off, remind them of it. help them. answer their questions. talk to them. u can be "strict" and be incredibly loving and be "cool". my mother kind of failed that, but, it made me realize what i see a good parent as. not to mention being free range is reserved for the wealthy. you have to protect your kid if u don't have much money or live in an iffy place and go to a bad school. i'm part japanese (born in us) but my family lives over there. little kids take the subway to school alone because it is safe and society values kids. they can only do that there. we don't build the us for that. mainland japanese parents are strict in the best way. i wish we could be like them. also cellphones are a slippery slope... but, if you're open with your child, they will tell you what's up anyway. maybe not the whole story, but, enough to let you know if they're safe. you can tell their emotions.
